# TypeScript Standards

## Critical tsconfig Flags

### `erasableSyntaxOnly: true`
Only TypeScript syntax that can be erased by stripping type annotations is allowed. This means:

```typescript
// ❌ Parameter properties — NOT allowed (applies to ANY access modifier)
class Foo {
  constructor(private readonly name: string) {}
}

// ✅ Declare field on the class body, assign in the constructor
class Foo {
  private readonly name: string
  constructor(name: string) {
    this.name = name
  }
}

// ✅ Same rule applies to Value Objects (no Entity base class)
class MatchConfig {
  private readonly props: MatchConfigProps   // field declaration
  private constructor(props: MatchConfigProps) {
    this.props = props                        // plain assignment
  }
}

// ❌ Regular enums — NOT allowed
enum Status { Active, Inactive }

// ✅ const enums or union types
type Status = 'active' | 'inactive'
```

### `verbatimModuleSyntax: true`
Every import used only as a type **must** use `import type`:

```typescript
// ❌ Will error if PointScorer is only used as a type
import { PointScorer } from './shared/types'

// ✅ Correct
import type { PointScorer } from './shared/types'

// ✅ Mixed — value + type from same module
import { Game, type GameType } from './game.entity'
```

### `noUnusedLocals` + `noUnusedParameters: true`
Remove unused variables and parameters. Use `_` prefix only when required by an interface/override:

```typescript
// ✅ Prefix with _ to suppress when intentionally unused
function handler(_event: MouseEvent): void { ... }
```

## Factory Method Pattern

All domain classes use `static create()` and `static restore()`:

```typescript
// create()  — brand-new instance, auto-generates UUID
const match = Match.create(team1, team2, config)

// restore() — rehydrates a persisted instance with a known id
const match = Match.restore(id, { team1, team2, config, ... })
```

## `import type` Discipline

- Use `import type` for all interfaces, type aliases, and enums used only as types
- Re-export types with `export type { Foo }` when needed

## Null Safety

- Prefer `null` over `undefined` for intentionally absent domain values (winner, currentGame, etc.)
- Use optional chaining (`?.`) and nullish coalescing (`??`) over explicit null checks when appropriate

## No Comments That Narrate Code

Only add comments that explain **why** something is done, never **what**:

```typescript
// ❌ Narrating
// Set the winner to team1
this.props.winner = 'team1'

// ✅ Explaining non-obvious intent
// noAd: at deuce (3-3), next point wins — no second chance
if (t1 >= 4 && t1 > t2) this.props.winner = 'team1'
```
